## 
## Step 1 â€“ Select an environment
After logging in at [https://cc.cloud.infinica.com/environments](https://cc.cloud.infinica.com/environments), select an **Organisation** from the list of collapsible items.

Click the desired **Environment** name to configure the environment. This will open the environment editor.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

## Step 2 â€“ Enter basic information
In the next step, enter some basic information for the environment.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- **Environment Name** â€“ Enter a descriptive name for the environment. This name will be used for the exported config file. Please note that only alphanumerical characters and dashes are allowed.

- **Platform** â€“ Select the platform on which to deploy the environment. The available options are:

Infinica Legacy (on-premise)

- Infinica Cloud Platform

- Doxee Platform 3

- **Platform Version** â€“ Select a release version of the selected platform. The end of support date for the selected release version is indicated on the right side of the version name (*nd* = not defined).

All available modules for the chosen platform and platform version are displayed in the lower part of the window. They can be enabled or disabled individually (default: enabled).

*NOTE: To get additional information about a specific module, hover over the module name with the cursor.*

## Step 3 â€“ Environment configuration
In the next step, the environment configuration can be customized. Mandatory fields are marked with an asterisk (*) and outlined in red.

![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAIAAAACCAMAAABFaP0WAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAGUExUReYSIwAAAM3dhWIAAAACdFJOU/8A5bcwSgAAAAlwSFlzAAAOwwAADsMBx2+oZAAAAAxJREFUGFdjAAIGBgAABgABr9uXpwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

To add additional configuration fields based on your needs, click on the green plus sign (+) in the tree navigation on the left side of the window.

![A close up of a word  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

If a default value is available for a configuration field, the text will be displayed in a gray color. In the example above, the fields â€˜*persistence_manager*â€™ and â€˜*schema*â€™ have set default values. It is possible to overwrite this value if needed.

A yellow warning sign will be displayed in the tree navigation next to configuration items with unfilled mandatory fields.

![A close-up of a sign  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

The available environment configuration fields change automatically when basic configurations in [Step 2](#_Step_2_â€“) are changed. For example, previously mandatory fields may become optional. In this case, a blue warning triangle is displayed next to previously mandatory fields.

![A close-up of a sign  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

It is possible to configure the subitems of some configuration fields individually. These are indicated by an **Override Fields** toggle.

Toggle the **Override Fields** option to display all subitems for which an individual value can be set. In the example below, the field â€˜activeâ€™ can be configured separately for the Process Engine and Content Repository configurations.

![A white background with black lines  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

## Step 4 â€“ Summary
When the environment configuration is complete, a summary displays the basic information that has been configured in [Step 2](#_Step_2_â€“).

The environment configurations can be exported as a ZIP file by clicking the **Export** button.

Select one of the available saving options

- **Save and Deploy Changes**

- **Save Changes without Deploying**

and click the **Finish** button to complete the configuration.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

A pop-up window allows to select or deselect optional additional export files:

- **Format for future import** â€“ Exports the environments configurations in a format that can be reimported to Command Center for further editing.

- **Include documentation** â€“ Includes the documentation in the exported configurations
